Absolutely! For large datasets with concurrent processing, an arena allocator can be more efficient by preallocating memory chunks. But then you have to remember to reset the arena or drain allocations if you want garbage-free reuse.

For sharing data between threads and supporting concurrency safely, `Arc<T>` (atomic reference counting) is better in Rust because it handles locking for thread-safe reference counting. Here's a snippet:

```rust
use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};

struct SharedData {
    records: Vec<Record>,
}

let data = Arc::new(Mutex::new(SharedData { records: vec![] }));
```
This way, you can safely clone the `Arc` across threads without worrying about race conditions and get thread-safe access to your dataset.

So, whether arenas or locks depends on your use case. If you’re not planning on parallelism yet, sticking with Rust’s ownership model and `Vec`s is cleaner. But if you foresee concurrency or want more precise control over memory allocations, arenas could be a good fit.
